urgh, Pa., were heard today by I\nthe commission of, the committee of!\none hundred investigating the Irish\nquestion. Miss MacSwiney told of in-I\n-cidetits surrounding the killing off\nLord Mayor MacCurtaln of Cork,!\nwhile Mr. Ouilfoil gave an eyewitness\naccount of a' military, raid on a small\ntown in County Claire, where he I\nvisited last summer. He said that!\nafter two police Officers had been!\nkilled, half a hundred of the military\ndescended upon the town and burned)\nand pillaged, ~it.\nI a of a ix so\nyattempt to force a priest to confess!\nto the murder of'two police,\" he said.\n\"They beat him with gun butts and'\nthen kicked Kim brutally. They\ncursed him and accused him of crimes\nbut the- prieBt maintained his .inno\ncence.\"\nThe military officers visited him.\nthe witness said, and threatened vio\nlence .until he displayed' his Ameri\ncan pasport. The raid hastened his\nreturn home, he said.\nf| AC OTA\nW CtEAKERS DYERS\n\u00abor b\u00abkot\nBoth' VhOBM IHfi\ntat OMha by fmd mt\n-CUT FLOWERS-\nFuneral Designs\nLovell Greenhouse\nFhoaa *30 SO* K. (th 1\nBLACK'S ICE\nwv'\nMinors Must:\nOf Pool Halls\nThe hw ajbilliat allowing\nminora to {requoat pool hails will.\nbe strictly enforeed In future nc\ncording to \u00abn announcement\nmade today by Henry O'Keefe,\nJr., pre*idcnt( the city com\nmission following an 'Informal\nmeeting ot fbp commlaBloQcrs.\nThe police liare been ordered\nto aoe that the l*w In this iWpcct\nis Strictly canted out, Mr. O'Seeto\nsaid, and In the event of viola\nlions prosecutions of a serious na\ntore will be Instituted against the\nproprietors of the places in\nvolved.\nMr O'Keefe states -that he\nwishes it strictly understood\nthat the city authorities \"raeau\nbusiness\" on thia point.\nXmas\nTrees are\nPlentiful Big\nShipments In\nThere is to be no dearth of Christ\nmas trees in Qrand Forka-this year,\nand every youngster- or grown-up who\nfinds a part of the holiday happiness,\nin a gaily decorated Christmas trey\nmay have his pick of a big selection\nright now.\nSome of the firnis which are'hand\nling the trees this'.year have had a\nnumber on sale during the last several,\ndays, but the larger amount of them,\nare Just beginning, to arrive. One of\nthe local wholesale houses today re\nceived a car-lot of Christmas trees in\nall sizes, from the Cass lake district.\nThe trees this year range oroUnd the\nusual prices for the various sizes, and\nthere is very little, if any increase in\nthe price, it is said.\nThe trees will be better this year,\nthan usual, it is believed, because of\nthe fact that weather conditions have\nmade the cutting of them easy. When\nour winter .seas.on arrives early, aijd\nthe snow in deep, cutting, is made diffi\ncult dye to tlva fact that it is hard to\nget into the groves, and the trees have\nto be cut, in most cases, above thfe'\nsnow banks. This .makes-''them of less\nattractive shape. The open weathfr\nthis year has made it easy to cut out\nthe choicest tp-ees. and even the small\nest\u2022 ones\u2022 coming in here arc in good!\nshape.\nOne of the firms 'here handling the'\ntrees sent members of its force into\nthe Bagley (Minn.) country, for two\ndays to cut a quantity of the trees,,\nwhich were hauled in here, for sale,\nabout ten days ago. These have been\ncarefully selected, and range in size,\nfrom the wee ones, to the very largo\nsizes, with prices graded accordingly.,'\nSERVICE MEN MAY\nRECEIVE VICTORY\nMEDALS HERE SOON\nAll former service men who have\nnot secured Victory medals may get\nthem without sending in their dis\ncharge papers on December 18 or 19\nwhen a. United States field clerk will\nbe in this city for the express purpose\nof taking applications *nd certifying\nhonorable discharges.\non those dates all men are request\ned to call at tle recruiting office, cor\nner of DeMers avenue and Fourth\nr.treet. where the clerk will be sta\ntioned.\nDo You Realize This?\nShopping Dpys to Christmas\nHere are attractive pric\nings on att